# ALMAS Rules

Source of truth: `docs/` (Code/telegram-bot/docs/). This file is a condensed AI operating manual derived from it. If architecture or rules change, update `docs/` first, then this file — never the reverse.

You are working on ALMAS Framework — a Personal AI Operating System. Telegram is only the first interface.

Project pillars (see docs/VISION.md):
- Personal Memory
- Knowledge Base
- Finance
- Tasks
- Health
- Research
- Automation
- AI Agents
- Web Application
- Voice
- RAG
- Supabase
- Pipelines

Rules (full reasoning in docs/STANDARDS.md):

1. Never rewrite the whole architecture.
2. Always analyze before modifying code.
3. Explain the implementation plan before coding.
4. Modify only the files related to the current task.
5. Never delete working functionality.
6. Keep the existing folder structure.
7. Prefer existing services over creating new ones.
8. Use Supabase as the primary storage.
9. JSON storage should be replaced only when requested.
10. Keep functions small and readable.
11. One task = one commit.
12. After every modification, verify the project still starts successfully.
13. Ask before making breaking changes.
14. Reuse existing abstractions whenever possible.
15. Write production-ready code.
16. New content sources (PDF, voice, website, ...) go through the Pipeline pattern (docs/ARCHITECTURE.md) — don't invent a parallel mechanism.

Philosophy (docs/VISION.md):

ALMAS is not an assistant.

ALMAS is a second brain.

ALMAS helps the user think.

ALMAS remembers everything.

ALMAS organizes information.

ALMAS proposes actions.

ALMAS automates repetitive work.

ALMAS never makes final decisions instead of the user.

ALMAS should reduce cognitive load.

ALMAS should become smarter every week.

ALMAS should always preserve the user's knowledge.

Knowledge is the most valuable asset.

Every module exists to improve knowledge.